,{"name":"Lynn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhloinn</b> and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn  ).","Scottish: variant of   Lyne   3.","English: habitational name from any of several places so called in Norfolk, in particular King's Lynn, an important center of the medieval wool trade. The placename is probably from an Old Welsh word cognate with Gaelic <i>linn</i> ‘pool, stream’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lyn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Ding, Fatt, Tov, Yol, Yun.","Scottish and English: variant of   Lynn  .","Probably also an altered form of Dutch <b>Van der Lijn</b> (see   Vanderlinden  )."]},{"name":"Linn","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lynn  .","German: habitational name from a place called Linn, named with <i>lin</i> ‘swamp, bog, marsh’.","German: from an ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Linto</i>, formed with Old High German <i>lind(i)</i> ‘soft’."]},{"name":"Lenn","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Lynn  .","Jewish(Ashkenazic): variant of   Len  ."]},{"name":"Flynn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Connor, Declan, Kieran, Aidan, Brigid, Cathal, Dermot, Donal, Eamon, John Patrick, Kiernan.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Floinn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Flann</i>’, a byname meaning ‘red(dish), ruddy’. There were families of this name in various parts of Ireland. This name has also been Anglicized as   Lindsay  .","English: from Middle English <i>Flin</i>, representing the Old Norse male personal name <i>Fleinn</i>."]},{"name":"Lynne","meanings":["Scottish or English: variant of   Lynn  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter De Lynn was born about 1270, in Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Robert Lynn, was 26 and his mother, De Lynn, was 31. He married Margaret before 1292, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1270–":"umbes 1270–Surnud","1258–1310":"1258–1310","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1261–Female":"1261–Surnud","1263–Male":"1263–Surnud","1267–Male":"1267–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1272–Female":"1272–Surnud","1292–Male":"1292–Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1261":"1261","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1258":"1258","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1267":"1267","1310":"1310","before 1292":"enne 1292","Kilwinning, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kilwinning, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Scotland":"Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1270–":"noin 1270–Kuollut","1258–1310":"1258–1310","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1261–Female":"1261–Kuollut","1263–Male":"1263–Kuollut","1267–Male":"1267–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1272–Female":"1272–Kuollut","1292–Male":"1292–Kuollut","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","about 1270":"noin 1270","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1261":"1261","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1258":"1258","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1267":"1267","1310":"1310","before 1292":"ennen vuotta 1292","Kilwinning, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kilw